canonical:
  title: 七月旣望有雨不泛舟翫月悵然有作
  author: 徐居正
  language: lzh
  text: 七月旣望月當白意欲泛舟擬赤壁造物小兒多戲劇年來於我苦相逼廣津水漲不可渡泥深馬滑箭橋路出門悵望入門愁奈此昏陰天又雨天上有月知幾秋赤壁之水萬古流天爲蘇仙有此夕江流月白仍泛舟當時豪氣盖乾坤一賦膾炙今猶存有舟不泛月不賞慷慨我欲牋天閽天心予奪不可知世間萬事多參差負舟負月吾奈何兩鬢颯爽生涼颸
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 七月旣望有雨不泛舟翫月悵然有作
  author: 徐居正
  language: lzh
  text: 七月旣望月當白。意欲泛舟擬赤壁。造物小兒多戲劇。年來於我苦相逼。廣津水漲不可渡。泥深馬滑箭橋路。出門悵望入門愁。奈此昏陰天又雨。天上有月知幾秋。赤壁之水萬古流。天爲蘇仙有此夕。江流月白仍泛舟。當時豪氣盖乾坤。一賦膾炙今猶存。有舟不泛月不賞。慷慨我欲牋天閽。天心予奪不可知。世間萬事多參差。負舟負月吾奈何。兩鬢颯爽生涼颸。
korean:
  title: 7월 기망에 비가 와서 배를 띄워 달을 구경하지 못하여 섭섭해서 지음
  author: 서거정
  language: kor
  text: |-
    칠 월 기망엔 달이 응당 밝으려니
    배를 띄워 적벽 놀이에 견주려 했더니
    조물주 어린애가 장난을 좋아해서
    연래로 나에게 몹시도 박해하누나
    광나루에 물이 넘쳐 건널 수 없고
    살다리 길은 몹시 질어 말이 미끄러지네
    문에 나서 원망스레 바라보며 문에 들어 수심하노니
    이 침침한 날씨 비조차 오는 것을 어찌하료
    하늘에 달 있는 지 몇 가을이 된고
    적벽강 물은 만고에 흘렀건만
    하늘이 소선을 위하여 오늘 저녁을 마련해
    흐르는 강물 밝은 달에 제대로 배를 띄웠었것다
    당시의 그 호기가 천지를 덮어
    만구에 외워 전하는 부한 편이 지금도 남아있네
    배 있어도 못 띄우고 달 구경도 못하니
    이 강개를 내가 하늘에게 물어보려네
    천심의 주고 앗음이야 알 수 없지만
    세상 만사가 어긋남이 많것다
    배도 달도 저버린 내 신세를 어쩌리
    두 귀밑머리에 서늘한 가을바람만 불어드네
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1400_010_0190&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: 'Seventh Month at Mid-Moon: Rain Prevents Me from Boating to Enjoy the Moon, and I Write This in Melancholy'
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Mid-autumn arrives, the moon should glow bright—
    I planned to drift my boat, imagining Red Cliff's delight.
    But fate, that playful child, delights in cruel games,
    and year after year it presses hard upon my aims.
    The broad ford swells beyond all crossing,
    the muddy paths leave horses slipping, bridges glossing.
    I step outside in longing, step within in sorrow—
    what can I do against this murk, this rain tomorrow?

    How many autumns since the moon has hung in heaven?
    Red Cliff's waters have flowed ten thousand years uneven.
    Yet Heaven granted that great sage his evening's gift—
    the river gleamed with moonlight as his boat did drift.
    In those days, such bold spirit covered all the land,
    and his famous rhapsody still stands, still grand.
    I have a boat unwaded, a moon unwatched and lost—
    what grievance can I lodge with Heaven, whatever the cost?

    Heaven's giving and taking, who can comprehend?
    The world's ten thousand things are crooked at the end.
    Boat and moon both stolen from me—what can I say?
    Just autumn winds that whisper through my temples gray.
  footnotes:
    - 'Red Cliff (赤壁): Reference to Su Shi''s famous "Rhapsody on Red Cliff" (赤壁賦), where the great Song poet enjoyed moonlit boating and achieved poetic immortality. Seo Geo-jeong positions himself against this celebrated precedent.'
    - 'Su the Sage (蘇仙): Su Shi, the 11th-century Song poet, revered for his literary genius and his legendary appreciation of nature.'
    - The playful frustration stems from the poet's inability to recreate Su Shi's celebrated moment—suggesting both personal disappointment and a meditation on fortune, inspiration, and the limits of human aspiration.
